05955nam a22007575i 9780824896508DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248965087 a10.1515/97808248965082doi  a(DE-B1597)644581  a(OCoLC)1371466890  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aDS799.9.K36 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a951.249223/eng/202302151 aLee, Anru, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHaunted Modernities :bGender, Memory, and Placemaking in Postindustrial Taiwan /cAnru Lee. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (246 p.) :b9 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Mediated Memory, Contested Space -- tPART I: Onset: Ownership of the Dead -- tChapter 1. The Death of Women Workers -- tChapter 2. The Significance of Insignificant People -- tPART II: Ghostscapes -- tChapter 3. Filial Daughters, Pious Ghosts -- tChapter 4. Subservient Women, Worker Heroines -- tChapter 5. Blue-Collar Industrial City, Blue-Color Ocean Capital -- tChapter 6. Supernatural Beings, Modernist State -- tPART III: Afterlife -- tChapter 7. Beyond the Memorial -- tEpilogue: Future Present, Future Past -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1973 twenty-five young women drowned in a ferry accident on their way to work in factories in Taiwan’s Kaohsiung Export Processing Zone. Their remains were recovered and interred collectively in what came to be called the Twenty-five Maiden Ladies Tomb. Without a husband’s ancestral hall where they would have been laid to rest, the spirits of these unmarried women were considered homeless and possibly vengeful, and so the Maiden Ladies Tomb was viewed as a place to be avoided—especially by young men traveling alone, fearful of encountering a female ghost searching for a husband. Over the years, numerous plans were made to revamp the tomb site; finally, in 2008, at the urging of local feminist communities, the Kaohsiung City government renovated the Twenty-five Maiden Ladies Tomb and renamed it the Memorial Park for Women Laborers. Haunted Modernities interrogates the nature of shared expressions of history, sentiments, and memory as it investigates the role of these women and other female workers in the shifting public narrative during and after the Maiden Ladies Tomb renovation. By exploring the ways in which the deceased young women were perceived to “haunt” the living and the diverse renovations recommended, the book illuminates how women workers in Taiwan have been conceptualized in the last several decades. In their proposals to renovate the tomb, the interested parties forged specific accounts of history, transforming the collective burial site according to varying definitions of “heritage” as Taiwan shifted to a postindustrial economy, where factory jobs were no longer the main source of employment. Their plans engaged with acts of remembering—communal and individual—to create new ways of understanding the present. The Twenty-five Maiden Ladies Tomb as a heritage site elucidates how “history” and “memory” are not simply about the past but part of a forward-looking process that emerges from the social, political, and economic needs of the present, legitimized and validated through its associations with the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryzTaiwanzKaohsiung City. 0aPublic opinionzTaiwanzKaohsiung City. 0aSingle womenzTaiwanzKaohsiung CityxPublic opinion. 0aWomenxEmploymentzTaiwanzKaohsiung CityxPublic opinion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh 